{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem asks for universal dimensionless constants related to the classicality of single-photon Hawking radiation. This involves analyzing the phase space, the action, and the relationship between the Hawking temperature and the characteristic frequency of the emitted radiation in the context of the semiclassical approximation.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "Identify and derive the first dimensionless constant related to the action of a single Hawking photon. Specifically, determine the value of the action S divided by the reduced Planck constant h_bar for a photon emitted at the characteristic Hawking frequency omega = kT/hbar. Show the derivation starting from the definition of the action in the Schwarzschild metric and verify if this constant is a universal integer or a specific transcendental value."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_2",
      "instructions": "Identify and derive the second dimensionless constant, which relates to the phase space volume or the density of states for a single-mode Hawking emission. Focus on the ratio of the characteristic wavelength of the Hawking radiation to the Schwarzschild radius, or the dimensionless coefficient in the expression for the entropy-to-area relation as it pertains to the emission of a single quantum. Provide a rigorous derivation and cross-verify with the Bekenstein-Hawking entropy framework."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_3",
      "instructions": "Identify and derive the third dimensionless constant, which characterizes the 'classicality' or the coherence of the radiation. This is typically defined by the ratio of the thermal wavelength to the gravitational radius or a specific coefficient in the Planck distribution that dictates the transition from quantum to classical regimes for a single photon. Ensure the value is dimensionless and consistent with the semiclassical limit of the Hawking temperature formula."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent agent will collect the three derived dimensionless constants from the helpers. It must ensure that all three values are dimensionless, universal (independent of the black hole mass), and represent the specific physical parameters governing the classicality of single-photon Hawking radiation. The final answer should be presented as a set of three values."
}

